---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';

const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'choosing-an-adapter', text: 'Choosing an adapter' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'indexeddb', text: 'IndexedDB' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'localstorage', text: 'localStorage' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'flushing-and-loading', text: 'Flushing and loading' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'offline-first', text: 'Offline-first patterns' },
];

const idb = `import { createLedger, collection } from 'ledger';
import { indexedDB } from 'ledger/adapters';

export const db = createLedger(
  {
    notes: collection<Note>({ key: 'id' }),
    tags: collection<Tag>({ key: 'id' }),
  },
  {
    persist: indexedDB({ name: 'notes-app', version: 1 }),
  }
);

// On first load, Ledger hydrates from disk before the store resolves:
await db.ready;`;

const ls = `import { localStorage } from 'ledger/adapters';

const db = createLedger(
  { settings: collection<Setting>({ key: 'key' }) },
  { persist: localStorage({ prefix: 'app:' }) }
);`;

const flush = `// Writes are buffered and flushed on the next microtask by default.
db.notes.insert(note);          // queued
await db.flush();               // force a write now

// Want write-through instead of buffered? Set debounce: 0.
indexedDB({ name: 'app', debounce: 0 });`;

const offline = `// Persisted stores are offline-first out of the box: reads and writes
// hit local storage, never the network. To sync with a server, push a
// changelog when you reconnect.
db.notes.onChange((change) => outbox.push(change));

window.addEventListener('online', () => flushOutbox());`;
---

<Docs
  title="Persistence"
  description="Keep Ledger data on the device with the IndexedDB and localStorage adapters."
  headings={headings}
>
  <span class="eyebrow">Guides</span>
  <h1>Persistence</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    By default a Ledger store lives in memory and resets on reload. Add a persistence
    adapter and your data survives refreshes, tab closes, and going offline — all
    without changing how you query.
  </p>

  <h2 id="choosing-an-adapter">Choosing an adapter</h2>
  <p>Two adapters ship in <code>ledger/adapters</code>. Pick based on how much data you keep:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Adapter</th><th>Best for</th><th>Capacity</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>indexedDB()</code></td><td>Records, lists, documents</td><td>Hundreds of MB+</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>localStorage()</code></td><td>Small settings &amp; flags</td><td>~5 MB</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="indexeddb">IndexedDB</h2>
  <p>
    The IndexedDB adapter is the default recommendation. It stores each collection in its own
    object store and hydrates the in-memory index when the store boots.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={idb} lang="ts" file="db.ts" />
  <div class="callout callout--warn">
    <span class="callout__icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <p>Always <code>await db.ready</code> before your first read on a persisted store, or you may query an empty index while hydration is still in flight.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="localstorage">localStorage</h2>
  <p>For a handful of preferences, the synchronous <code>localStorage</code> adapter is simpler and needs no <code>await</code>:</p>
  <CodeBlock code={ls} lang="ts" />

  <h2 id="flushing-and-loading">Flushing and loading</h2>
  <p>
    Writes are batched and flushed automatically on the next microtask, so a burst of inserts
    becomes one disk write. You can force or tune this:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={flush} lang="ts" />

  <h2 id="offline-first">Offline-first patterns</h2>
  <p>
    A persisted Ledger store is already offline-first — nothing it does touches the network.
    To replicate to a backend, subscribe to changes and drain an outbox when you reconnect:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={offline} lang="ts" />
  <div class="callout callout--note">
    <span class="callout__icon" aria-hidden="true">ℹ️</span>
    <p>Ledger gives you the local half of sync (durable storage + a change feed). The remote half — conflict resolution and transport — is intentionally yours to own.</p>
  </div>
</Docs>
